an important topic in the book and is a key focus in the 17 chapters. The book is divided into two large blocks, the first one consisting of case studies (8 chapters) and the second with features complexes (9 chapters). The former look at major anglophone locations from an areal perspective while the latter examine linguistic categories and features with a view to determine whether these could be areally based or not.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aDialectology.  aEnglish.1 aAnderwald, Lieselotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnsaldo, Umberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrato, Thorsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBritain, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurridge, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, J. K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Matthew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGramley, Stephan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHickey, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHickey, Raymond, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHuber, Magnus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLim, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLunkenheimer, Kerstin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaguire, Warren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaier, Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 